# TypeScript Naming & Type Standards

## Naming Conventions (Microsoft + Google)

| Item | Convention | Example |
|------|-----------|---------|
| Components | PascalCase | `CustomerCard` |
| Hooks | `use` + camelCase | `useCustomerData` |
| Utilities/functions | camelCase | `formatCurrency` |
| Types & Interfaces | PascalCase | `CustomerData` |
| Component props | `{Name}Props` | `CustomerCardProps` |
| Enum values | PascalCase | `Status.Active` |
| Constants (module-level) | SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE | `MAX_RETRIES` |
| Store files | camelCase + `Store` | `kundenStore.ts` |

- âťŚ Do NOT prefix interfaces with `I` (no `ICustomer`, no `IProps`)
- âťŚ Do NOT prefix private items with `_` unless truly private class member
- âś… Use `undefined` instead of `null` (Microsoft TypeScript rule)
- âś… One component per file; file name matches the component name

## interface vs type

Use `interface` for component props only:
```typescript
// âś…
interface CustomerCardProps {
  id: string
  name: string
  onClick: () => void
}
```

Use `type` for everything else (hooks, utilities, API responses, unions):
```typescript
// âś…
type UseCustomerDataReturn = {
  data: CustomerData | undefined
  isLoading: boolean
  hasError: boolean
}

type CustomerStatus = 'active' | 'inactive' | 'pending'
```

Use `Pick`, `Omit`, `Extract` to avoid duplicating types:
```typescript
type PublicCustomer = Omit<Customer, 'password' | 'internalNotes'>
```

## Imports

- Use named imports â€” never `import * as X`
```typescript
// âś…
import { formatCurrency, formatDate } from 'common/utils'

// âťŚ
import * as utils from 'common/utils'
```

- Use `index.ts` barrel files for clean feature imports:
```typescript
// âś…
import { CustomerCard } from 'pages/customers'

// âťŚ
import { CustomerCard } from 'pages/customers/components/CustomerCard/CustomerCard'
```

## Comments & Documentation

- No comments that describe what the code does â€” only explain **why**
- Use `/** @todo */` (JSDoc style) for future work
- Use `/** @see URL */` for browser quirks or API workarounds
- Use JSDoc for all exported utilities and hooks:
```typescript
/**
 * Formats a value as Euro currency for display in the German locale.
 * @see https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Intl/NumberFormat
 */
export const formatEuro = (value: number): string =>
  new Intl.NumberFormat('de-DE', { style: 'currency', currency: 'EUR' }).format(value)
```
